ce:section.ce:para:
The application of synthesized smart hydrogel in Fe3+ sensing has been explored. Under optimum conditions, as shown in Fig. 5
                        a, the PL intensity quenching of the smart hydrogel with increasing Fe3+ ion concentration (0–140 μM) was observed. As the concentration of Fe3+ ions increase, the PL emission of smart hydrogel under 360 nm excitation correspondingly changed from bright blue to weak blue (inset in Fig. 5a). In addition, a good linear relationship between PL relative intensity (F0/F) and Fe3+ ion concentration in a wide range from 10 μM to 100 μM was obtained. The detection limit (S/N = 3) was estimated to be 65 nM (3s/k, in which s was the standard deviation for the blank solution, and k was the slope of the calibration curve) (Fig. 5b–c), which was much lower than recently published assays based on CDs from different precursors (shown in Table 1
                        ) [37]. In order to evaluate the selectivity of the obtained smart hydrogel to Fe3+ ion, the fluorescence response of smart hydrogel to different metal ions was investigated. As demonstrated in Fig. S9, a good selectivity of smart hydrogel towards Fe3+ ion over other metal ions (Co2+, Al3+, Cu2+, Hg2+, Ca2+, Fe2+, Ba2+, Mg2+, Cr3+, Pb2+, and Ni2+) was observed. Overall, the fluorescent smart hydrogel exhibited a good selectivity and sensitivity towards Fe3+ ion and could be used as a good sensor for Fe3+ ion detection.
